**The key idea is:**
If the grid has a solution, we can arrive at the solution by looking only at the first row and the first column. This happens because each solution step moves the entire row or entire column.

**How to know if the table has a solution?**
The dimensions are dependent, so we need to check that when correcting the first row or first column, the values in the middle of the table are resolved too.

The code below shows how we analyze this:
```c++
for (int i=1; i<board.size(); i++) {
    for (int j=1; j<board[i].size(); j++) {
        if (((board[0][0] ^ board[i][0]) ^ (board[i][j] ^ board[0][j])) == 1) {
            return -1;
        }
    }
}
```

This code compares whether the middle value has the same parity with the edge values.

[![Image from Gyazo](https://i.gyazo.com/1dc9dbe67d99ded468cd73efb0a2a03e.png)](https://gyazo.com/1dc9dbe67d99ded468cd73efb0a2a03e)

- if the blue cells have different values, the green cells must also have different values.
- if blue cells have equal values, green cells must also have equal values.

If neither of the above two conditions are true, we have a table that is impossible to solve. 
This looks like magic right? Let's look at the solved table:
<p>
<img src="https://i.gyazo.com/f3e3ee7360a38024e12ef928fef72cc9.png" width="30%">
</p>

Between two adjacent lines, one is the conjugate of the other and the same applies for columns. When we swap a row or a column from an solved table, we have two scenarios:

1. Swap identical row or collumn
2. Swap conjugated row or collumn

No matter how many operations you do, we will always fall into these two scenarios. In summary, the code above checks if the current table has this property.

Before calculating the number of steps to reach the solution. We need to do one more validation, this one is much simpler.

This validation consists of counting the number of 1s and 0s in the first row and in the first column:
```c++
for (int i=0; i<N; i++) {
	if (board[0][i]) onesInFirstRow++;
	else zerosInFirstRow++;

	if (board[i][0]) onesInFirstCol++;
	else zerosInFirstCol++;
}

if (abs(onesInFirstRow - zerosInFirstRow) > 1) return -1;
if (abs(onesInFirstCol - zerosInFirstCol) > 1) return -1;
```

- If the difference between zeros and ones is greater than 1, it's impossible solve this table.


Now to calculate the minimum number of steps, we need to solve the first column and the first row individually and sum each result.

**Solving to first row and column**

To solve this, we have two scenarios:
1. N even
2. N odd

When N is even, we have two solutions:

- **[0,1,...,0,1]** (starting with 0)
- **[1,0,...,1,0]** (starting with 1)


We know that each swap can fix two elements as we can see in the example below:

- **[0,0,1,1]**  --> **[0,1,0,1]**  (swap second with third item)

So, the number of moviments needed to transform a row or a collumn to any two possible solution is:

- number of wrong elements divided by 2

As one solution is the inverse of the other, we can say that:

- **solution_start_one** = N - **solution_start_zero**

Therefore, when N is even, the answer will be the smallest value between the two possible solutions.

```c++
// This for compare the first row and column 
// with the solution that starts with one
for (int i=0; i<N; i++) {
	if (board[0][i] == i%2) rowMovesNeeded++;
	if (board[i][0] == i%2) colMovesNeeded++;
} 

if (N % 2 == 0) {
	colMovesNeeded = min(colMovesNeeded, N-colMovesNeeded);
	rowMovesNeeded = min(rowMovesNeeded, N-rowMovesNeeded);

	return (colMovesNeeded + rowMovesNeeded) / 2;
} 

// solve when N is odd
```

When N is odd, we have only one solution:

- **[1,0,..,0,1]** (when the row or column has more ones)
- **[0,1,..,1,0]** (when the row or column has more zeros)

If we have more zeros, we only use the value to solution that begin with zero. So with odd N we need analyze the number of zeros and use the correct solution to each case.

```c++
if (onesInFirstCol < zerosInFirstCol) {
	colMovesNeeded = N - colMovesNeeded;
}

if (onesInFirstRow < zerosInFirstRow) {
	rowMovesNeeded = N - rowMovesNeeded;
}

return (colMovesNeeded + rowMovesNeeded) / 2;
```

