solutions.content:
when the size of the array is odd the number of maximums(peaks) we need is **NH= floor(n/2)** wheras the number of valleys we need is **NL = floor(n/2)+1 elements.**
when the size of the array is even the number of peaks and valleys are equals **NH=NL=n/2**
so we sort the array 1st then for valleys we need the first NL elements elements i.e **a[0,1,...,NL-1]** and for the peaks we need **a[NH,..,N]**
To avoid the compilication of repeating elements occuring together we start filling the elements from the back i.e
for valleys we fill in order NL-1-> NL-2 -> ... -> 0
for peaks we fill in order N-1 -> N-2 .... -> NL
```
class Solution {
public:
    void wiggleSort(vector<int>& a) {
        int i,n=a.size();
        int l=0,h=n/2,mx=-1,mn=INT_MAX;
        sort(a.begin(),a.end());
        if(n&1)
            h++;
        i=h;
        l=h-1;
        h=n-1;
        vector<int> ans;
        while(1){
            if(l<0&&h<i)
                break;
            if(l>=0)
                ans.push_back(a[l--]);
            if(h>=i)
                ans.push_back(a[h--]);
        }
        for(i=0;i<n;i++)
            a[i]=ans[i];       
    }
};
```

