1. Virtual Indexing: By accessing the array with m(i) if the array is partial sorted into 3 sets. **[<median][median][>median]**. m(i) will take care of alternately arranging elements of the array into odd and even locations

2. Generating [<median][median][>median]: Running quicksort with partial calls i.e only the side of the pivot which has median is recursed on instead of both sides. Median is returned in O(n) average complexity
3. For cases where multiple numbers are present with median value, for the algo. to work they must all be in the together in the middle of our partially sorted array
ex. 5 5 5 1 6
must be 1 5 5 5 6
and not 5 1 5 6 5
So the generic quick sort partition module must be modified to always partition in a way that pivot equivalent numbers come to the middle of the array. This is done by running two pointers from low and high for swapping.

'''

	import random

	def partition(nums, low, high):

		pi = random.randint(low, high)
		pivot = nums[m(pi)]

		i = low         # points to smaller elements cur idx
		j = high
		k = low
		while k <= j:
			if nums[m(k)] > pivot:
				nums[m(k)], nums[m(i)] = nums[m(i)], nums[m(k)]
				i += 1
				k += 1
			elif nums[m(k)] < pivot:
				nums[m(k)], nums[m(j)] = nums[m(j)], nums[m(k)]
				j -= 1
			else:
				k += 1

		return i, j


	def quicksort(nums, low, high, median):

		while True:
			pi, pj = partition(nums, low, high)
			if pi <= median <= pj:
				return
			elif median < pi:
				high = pi - 1
			elif median > pj:
				low = pj + 1

		return

	def m(i):
		return (1 + 2*i) % (N | 1)

	class Solution:
		def wiggleSort(self, nums: List[int]) -> None:
			global N
			N = len(nums)
			quicksort(nums, 0, len(nums)-1, len(nums)//2)
'''

