@MuMustafa95  had [this](https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-repeating-character-replacement/discuss/934637/Clear-concise-C%2B%2B-solution-no-explanation-needed-(Sliding-window-better-than-99-time-O(n))) great solutions, I want to add an explanation to things that might look strange
```
class Solution {
public:
    int characterReplacement(string s, int k) {
        int right = 0, left = 0, maxLetter = 0;
        int alphabet[26] = {0};
        while(right < s.length()){
            alphabet[s[right] - 'A']++;
            maxLetter = max(maxLetter, alphabet[s[right] - 'A']);
            right++;

            if(right - left - maxLetter > k){
                alphabet[s[left] - 'A']--;
                left++;
            }
        }
        return right - left;
    }
};
```

**What are the strange things?**
1) You don't update your `maxLetter` 
2) You don't mantain a result length, simply return `right - left` at the end.

This works because of the following:
**Longest substing must have the maximum `maxLetter`.**
- you best result is `(maxLetter + k)`,
- k stays the same for any substring so `maxLetter` must be the maximum over all `maxLetter`s you encountered during runtime.

**Why the wrong `maxLetter` won't mess your result?**
- if your `maxLetter` is bigger than it should be, you gonna skip left increments and make your current valid substring longer than it actually is
- it doesn't matter since you gonna return the length of the longest, and we showed that it's `maxLetter` is gonna be correct

**Why it's enough to return `right-left`?**
- will always grow, so we might make `right` larger and wrongly inflate our output
- if `maxLetter` doesn't grow along with `right`, `left` is gonna grow as well!! (offsetting the mistaken `right` growth)
- this way the `right - left` gap is the actual longest substring

Hope this helps

