solutions.content:
I would like to add a key observation on why this works and most importantly, why the inner `while` that you see in other solutions should be replaced with an `if` instead. No offense to anyone, but I think whoever uses an inner `while` loop has not fully understood the algorithm. That loop is executed at most once anyway, and understanding why is important in order to explain the algorithm to the interviewer successfully.

Once we get a **valid, new and longer** window two things can happen at the next iteration:

* we can get a even longer window, and in this case things are straigforward. The `maxFreq` will be equal to the `maxFreq` of the previous iteration `+1`. Why? We can extend the string only by adding a character that is the same as the most frequent one, otherwise we break the window rule.

* we are not able to extend the window. So are we going to shrink it now and make it valid again? **NO!**. I bet that's what most of the people think when they see that inner `while` loop. In fact they ask why isn't the `maxFreq` updated? What happens instead, is that we want to move the window just one step to the right. When we increment both `left` and `right` by one, we basically keep the window of the same size and slide it by one step.


You might ask now two questions:

* Why moving one step to the right is enough (without shrinking the window)? Answer: We have a "longest" window already so finding another one of the same size is not helpful. Yeah, we might shrink the window, then extend it, then find another window of the same size as `longest` but in the end we will see no improvement as long as it it's just as long as `longest`.

* Ok, so you are going to keep the window of the same size and move it to the right. Isn't there a risk at some point to have characters in your window that break the rule of "at most k replacements"? Answer: Yes, we might have an invalid window of size `longest` but the good news is that this is not "harmful" for us. The `Math.max` statement has no effect if we keep doing `Math.max(longest, longest)`.  However, **once the window will move enough to the right to become valid again, we will be able to extend it (if possible)**.  In other words, we will only extend a **valid** window. That's why shrinking the window is not necessary, because we want to find **another window that is just as long `longest` AND that can be extended**.

Hope this was helpful and made the algorithm more intuitive for you :)

Finally, here is the code

```
class Solution {
    public int characterReplacement(String s, int k) {
        int freq[] = new int['Z' - 'A' + 1];
        int left = 0, right = 0, longest = 0, maxFreq = 0;

        while(right < s.length()) {
            char rightChar = s.charAt(right);
            freq[rightChar - 'A']++;
            maxFreq = Math.max(maxFreq, freq[rightChar - 'A']);
            right++;

            if(right - left - maxFreq <= k) {
                longest = Math.max(longest, right - left);
            }

            if(right - left - maxFreq > k) {
                char leftChar = s.charAt(left);
                freq[leftChar - 'A']--;
                left++;
            }
        }

        return longest;
    }
}
```

