solutions.content:
Well, This problem is an intresting one. 

Objective is:
Find a longest substring where you can replace only k chars with another character and it becomes all repeating characters.

Approach:
As its sliding window, you need left and right index variables.

1. Start scanning by increment right.

2. Maintain a character count strategy by hashmap or arrays etc.

3. Maintain a variable **maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar** containg the value of a character which got encountered most number of time.

4. If we have a window where we can replace k or less than k characters other than maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar character  then its a candidate for max window size, 
or 
Window Size - maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar <= k

	for example,
if you have string AAABBC and k = 2
A    A    A   B   B  C
^&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;^
Left&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Right
maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar = 3
k = 2
Window Size = 4
4 - 3 <= 2  --> this holds true

Here we can replace B with A and windo size 4 is the candidate for max window,

5. Once you find while scanning that the equation
(maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar + k (not of replacable characers) = Window Size 
does not hold true.

	i .e. you have  k+1 different character Other than maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar then you need to increment left.

	Example.
if you have string AAABBCAAA and k = 2
A    A    A   B   B  C
^&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;^
Left&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Right

	Now 
maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar = 3 (count of A)
Other Character Count = 3  (Count of B and C)
Window size = 6
3 + 2 = 6  --> This does not hold true.

Now, increment left untill you find the sutiable window again, where our equation 
	Window Size - maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar <= k holds true. 
	for example,

if you have string AAABBCAAA and k = 2
A    A    A   B   B  C
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ^&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ^
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Left&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Right
We need to incremnet till we find a window where we can replace 2 character and find another suitable candidate.

doing so maintain the max window you encountered.

Sample code,

```
public int characterReplacement(String s, int k)
   {
      int left = 0, right = 0, maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar = 0;

      int maxWindowKReplacableCharSize = 0;

      // A map to count characters encountered during traversal
      Map<Character, Integer> charCountMap = new HashMap<Character, Integer>();

      // Traverse Untill the end
      while (right < s.length())
      {
         char currentChar = s.charAt(right);

         // Increment the count for current character
         int currentCharCount = 1 + charCountMap.getOrDefault(currentChar, 0);

         // Update in the character count map
         charCountMap.put(currentChar, currentCharCount);

         // Check if the current char is the max occuring character
         maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar = Math.max(maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar, currentCharCount);

         // Initialize the window size
         int windowSize = right - left + 1;

         // This compaision tells that if we have a window where there are at most
         // k character other than maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar.
         // If those k character are replaced then its a candidate window for the solution.
         if (windowSize - maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar <= k)
         {
            // If the candidate window is the max window, then update the window.
            maxWindowKReplacableCharSize = Math.max(maxWindowKReplacableCharSize, windowSize);
         }

         // Start sliding the window from left untill we arrive at a situation from
         // where we can start looking for the pattern again.
         // i.e increment left untill we arrive at a position where window contains
         // k replacable characters other than the maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar

         while (windowSize - maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar > k)
         {
            char poppedChar = s.charAt(left);
            // While sliding from the left reduce the count of character which is removed.
            charCountMap.put(poppedChar, charCountMap.get(poppedChar) - 1);

            // **NOTE**
            // Ideally we should be recalculating the the max reoccuring character (maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar) again,
            // as we are reducing the count of the character.
            // We can do that and still the solution will work, but it will be needless step.
            // As to the context of the problem we already have found,
            // (max reoccuring character) while scanning.
            // Now the result max window will only update if we find a character (same or diffrent) which is
            // occuring more than max reoccuring character (maxCountForMostRepetetiveChar).
            // This will be autocalcuated while scanning the array at line 30.
            // This took some time to understand.

            // Slide the window from left
            left++;
            windowSize = right - left + 1;
         }

         // Slide the window from right
         right++;
      }
      return maxWindowKReplacableCharSize;
   }
   ```

The solution can be futher optimzed to use arrays insted of maps and reducing the number of variable i've taken for explanation for better timing calculations.

Something like,

